---
import { withBase } from '../../lib/url';
import Prose from '../../layouts/Prose.astro';
import QuoteList from '../../components/QuoteList.astro';
import { TECHNIQUES } from '../../lib/techniques';

const t = TECHNIQUES.find((x) => x.slug === 'aspects-and-company')!;
---

<Prose
  title={t.title}
  description={t.description}
  crumbs={[{ name: 'Techniques', href: '/techniques/' }, { name: t.title }]}
  kicker="Technique"
  jsonLd={[{ '@type': 'Article', headline: t.title }]}
>
  <p>
    The houses of the chart behold one another as the signs do: each house has its sextiles,
    squares and trines on either side, and its opposition across the chart. Aspects falling
    <em>against</em> the natural order of the houses are called <em>dexter</em> and are the
    stronger; those following the order are <em>sinister</em>. Figures, like planets, also keep
    friendships and enmities with one another, by their rulers and by their elements:
  </p>
  <QuoteList topic="aspects" />
  <p>
    Friendly figures aspecting the house of the question aid it; hostile figures hinder it.
    Crowley's worked example shows the weighing of these findings in practice:
    <a href={withBase('/library/crowley/method-of-judging/')}>the General Method of Judging a Figure</a>.
  </p>
  <h2>The company of figures</h2>
  <p>
    Beside the aspects, neighbouring houses keep <em>company</em>: the second with the first, the
    fourth with the third, and so through the chart. Cattan distinguishes simple, half-simple and
    compound company, and judges by them with worked examples from his own practice:
  </p>
  <QuoteList topic="company" />
</Prose>
